<h3 class="wp-block-heading wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio" id="High-Knees">High Knees</h3>



<p class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/high-knees" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">High knees</a> are a high-intensity cardiovascular exercise that combines <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0281737" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">lower-body strength and core engagement </a>with dynamic, rhythmic movement. This exercise primarily targets the quadriceps, hamstrings, calves, and hip flexors while also activating the core and upper body.</p>



<p class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio">Performing high knees improves cardiovascular endurance and burns significant calories, making it effective for weight loss and overall fitness. This movement enhances <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2095254616301004" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">running</a> form by promoting proper posture, knee drive, and foot placement, which benefit athletes and casual runners.</p>



<p class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><a href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Karuppasamy-Govindasamy/publication/383721912_Effectiveness_of_High-Intensity_Circuit_Training_on_Physical_Fitness_Among_Athletes_A_Systematic_Review_of_Randomized-Controlled_and_Non-Controlled_Trials/links/66ff55a7b753fa724d5872a9/Effectiveness-of-High-Intensity-Circuit-Training-on-Physical-Fitness-Among-Athletes-A-Systematic-Review-of-Randomized-Controlled-and-Non-Controlled-Trials.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">High knees</a> strengthen the hip flexors, forefoot, and toe muscles, contributing to better balance and stability. The exercise also develops speed and agility by mimicking sprinting mechanics in a controlled, stationary format. These benefits translate to improved functionality in everyday activities and athletic performance.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo vimeo-custom wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="High Knees" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980217278?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">High Knee Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio">How To Do</h4>



<ol type="video" class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio">
<li>Stand with your feet hip-width apart.</li>



<li>Lift your right knee to your chest while simultaneously raising your left arm.</li>



<li>Quickly switch to lift your left knee and right arm.</li>



<li>Continue alternating legs and arms in a running motion.</li>



<li>Keep a rapid pace, staying on the balls of your feet.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio">Tips</h4>



<ul type="video" class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio">
<li>Maintain an upright posture with your core engaged.</li>



<li>Aim to bring your knees up to at least hip height.</li>



<li>Keep your arms bent at 90 degrees and pump them vigorously.</li>



<li>Land softly on the balls of your feet to reduce impact.</li>



<li>Start with shorter intervals and gradually increase duration as you build endurance.</li>
</ul>



